    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

     <insight>
        <p>
            The quadratic formula is a universal method for solving quadratic equations of the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>
            , particularly when factoring is difficult or impossible. 
            
        </p>
        <p>
            It is derived from the "completing the square" method and provides a direct way to find the roots of any quadratic equation, regardless of whether the coefficients are rational or irrational.
        </p>
        <p>
            The formula is given by:
            <m>x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are coefficients from the quadratic equation.
        </p>
        <p>
            The discriminant, <m>b^2 - 4ac</m>, determines the nature of the roots:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    If the discriminant is positive, there are two distinct real roots.
                </li>
                <li>
                    If the discriminant is zero, there is exactly one real root (a repeated root).
                </li>
                <li>
                    If the discriminant is negative, there are no real roots, but two complex conjugate roots.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>How to apply quadratic equation</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Arrange all terms to one side to set the equation to zero: <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Identify the values of the coefficients <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> from the quadratic equation.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Substitute the values of <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> into the quadratic formula.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Solve for <m>x</m> by simplifying the expression under the square root, ensuring to calculate both the plus and minus scenarios
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the quadratic equation <m>2x^2 - 4x - 6 = 0</m> using the quadratic formula.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, identify the coefficients: <m>a = 2</m>, <m>b = -4</m>, and <m>c = -6</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Next, substitute these values into the quadratic formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    x = \frac{-(-4) \pm \sqrt{(-4)^2 - 4(2)(-6)}}{2(2)}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplify the expression under the square root:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    x = \frac{4 \pm \sqrt{16 + 48}}{4}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    x = \frac{4 \pm \sqrt{64}}{4}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    x = \frac{4 \pm 8}{4}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                This gives us two solutions:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    x = \frac{4 + 8}{4} = 3
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                and
            </p>
            <p> 
                <m>
                    x = \frac{4 - 8}{4} = -1
                </m>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve: 
                <m>
                    x^2 + 6x + 10 = 0                               
                </m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Identify the coefficients: <m>a = 1</m>, <m>b = 6</m>, and <m>c = 10</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Substitute into the quadratic formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    x = \frac{-6 \pm \sqrt{6^2 - 4(1)(10)}}{2(1)}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplify the expression under the square root:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> x \amp = \frac{-6 \pm \sqrt{36 - 40}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> x =\amp \frac{-6 \pm \sqrt{-4}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x =\amp \frac{-6 + \sqrt{-4}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x =\amp \frac{-6 - \sqrt{-4}}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>     
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A ball is thrown upward from <m>20</m> meters high with an initial velocity of <m>15</m> m/s. Its height <m>h</m>  after <m>t</m>
                 seconds is <m>h= -5t^2 + 15t + 20</m> . After how many seconds does the ball hit the ground? 

            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find when the ball hits the ground, we set <m>h = 0</m> and solve for <m>t</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    -5t^2 + 15t + 20 = 0
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Divide the entire equation by 5 to simplify:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    t^2 - 3t - 4 = 0
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Identify the coefficients: <m>a = 1</m>, <m>b = -3</m>, and <m>c = -4</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Substitute into the quadratic formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    t = \frac{-(-3) \pm \sqrt{(-3)^2 - 4(1)(-4)}}{2(1)}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Simplify the expression under the square root:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    t = \frac{3 \pm \sqrt{9 + 16}}{2}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    t = \frac{3 \pm \sqrt{25}}{2}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since the discriminant is positive, there are two real solutions:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    t = \frac{3 + 5}{2} = 4
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                and
            </p>
            <p> 
                <m>
                    t = \frac{3 - 5}{2} = -1
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since time cannot be negative, the ball hits the ground after <m>4</m> seconds.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example> 

